70.title: Zermelo-Fraenkel provability Oracle
70.text:
The Zermelo-Fraenkel provability Oracle is a [thought experiment] illustrating an extreme case of a narrowly [Boxed](ai_boxing-2) machine intelligence, wrapped in multiple layers of software simulation, that can only output purported proofs of prespecified theorems in Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory at prespecified times, which proofs are then routed to a Boxed [proof-verifier] which checks the proof to make sure all the derivations follow syntactically, and then the verifier outputs a 0 or 1 saying whether the prespecified theorem was proven from the Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms.  Unfortunately it's not clear what pivotal achievement could be carried out using this final result.

The main point of the thought experiment is that while you might in principle be able to Box an AI so thoroughly that it would be safe even if it were superintelligent (hardware inside a Faraday cage working on an independent power supply, multiple layers of software emulation, and the entire Box reducing to a single bit that can be output only at a prespecified time, maybe with the chamber being destroyed by explosives afterwards, etctera), *and* be able to trust the result if the proof verifier is sufficiently simple and sufficiently thoroughly verified and its code is not known to the AI in advance, it's hard to see how the knowledge gained could be [pivotal](pivotal-1) to [value achievement](ValueAchievementDilemma-1).  There's no known way to save the world, if only we could know for certain that a prespecified theorem had a proof in Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory.

This is an extreme-case illustration of how restricting an AI enough to make it safe can also restrict it so much that it is no longer relevant to the larger dilemma.
